l records, Spirits of the Rockies is a sophisticated account of the situation that these Indigenous communities encountered when they were denied access to the Banff National Park. Courtney W. Mason examines the power relations and racial discourses that dominated the eastern slopes of the Canadian Rocky Mountains and shows how the Nakoda strategically used the Banff Indian Days festivals to gain access to sacred lands and respond to colonial policies designed to repress their cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAssiniboine IndiansxColonizationxAlbertaxBanff National Park. 0aAssiniboine IndiansxColonizationzAlbertazBanff National Park. 0aAssiniboine IndiansxEconomic conditionsxAlbertaxBanff National Park. 0aAssiniboine IndiansxHistoryxAlbertaxBanff National Park. 0aAssiniboine IndiansxSocial conditionsxAlbertaxBanff National Park. 0aAssiniboine IndianszAlbertazBanff National ParkxEconomic conditions. 0aAssiniboine IndianszAlbertazBanff National ParkxHistory. 0aAssiniboine IndianszAlbertazBanff National ParkxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aGetty, Ian A.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRollinmud, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261991340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442619913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442619913.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles